<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="95" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[189,798,545,712]" lastBlockId="1.[835,1443,225,711]" pageId="1" pageNumber="95">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,258,652,676]" pageId="1" pageNumber="95">Male.</emphasis>
Forewing length 
<quantity box="[479,554,652,676]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="95" unit="mm" value="5.0">5 mm</quantity>
. General color dark brown to black. Epiproct long and slender, forming a narrow triangular structure in dorsal aspect (
<figureCitation box="[1363,1426,225,249]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="1.[189,241,1434,1458]" captionTargetBox="[218,1459,785,1346]" captionTargetId="figure-422@1.[613,968,793,1346]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Figs. 1-3. Perlomyia ainu terminalia. 1. Male dorsal. 2. Male ventral. 3. Male lateral." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4760798" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4760798/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="95">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
), and shaped like a raptorial beak in lateral aspect (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="1.[189,241,1434,1458]" captionTargetBox="[218,1459,785,1346]" captionTargetId="figure-422@1.[613,968,793,1346]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Figs. 1-3. Perlomyia ainu terminalia. 1. Male dorsal. 2. Male ventral. 3. Male lateral." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4760798" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4760798/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="95">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). Tergum 9 broadly excavated on posterior margin; small knobs absent from tergum 10, but posterolateral margins developed into low wide mounds. Tergum 8 with small, erect median lobe truncate on posterior margin and tergum 6 with a minute posteromedian lobe. Cerci bear a small posteromedian spine in lateral aspect (
<figureCitation box="[1350,1428,509,533]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="1.[189,241,1434,1458]" captionTargetBox="[218,1459,785,1346]" captionTargetId="figure-422@1.[613,968,793,1346]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Figs. 1-3. Perlomyia ainu terminalia. 1. Male dorsal. 2. Male ventral. 3. Male lateral." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4760798" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4760798/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="95">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). Paraprocts fused into a broad, thick process; lateral aspect of paraprocts wide at base and tapered to form a sagittate structure in ventral aspect (
<figureCitation box="[1360,1429,615,640]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="1.[189,241,1434,1458]" captionTargetBox="[218,1459,785,1346]" captionTargetId="figure-422@1.[613,968,793,1346]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Figs. 1-3. Perlomyia ainu terminalia. 1. Male dorsal. 2. Male ventral. 3. Male lateral." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4760798" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4760798/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="95">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
). Apex of sternum 9 curved strongly dorsad (
<figureCitation box="[1360,1427,651,675]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="1.[189,241,1434,1458]" captionTargetBox="[218,1459,785,1346]" captionTargetId="figure-422@1.[613,968,793,1346]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Figs. 1-3. Perlomyia ainu terminalia. 1. Male dorsal. 2. Male ventral. 3. Male lateral." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4760798" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4760798/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="95">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
); vesicle wide apically and tapered to base (
<figureCitation box="[1358,1429,686,711]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="1.[189,241,1434,1458]" captionTargetBox="[218,1459,785,1346]" captionTargetId="figure-422@1.[613,968,793,1346]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Figs. 1-3. Perlomyia ainu terminalia. 1. Male dorsal. 2. Male ventral. 3. Male lateral." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4760798" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4760798/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="95">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
